  "body": "{\"query\":\"OWASP authentication session management payment security checklist web application official\",\"follow_up_questions\":null,\"answer\":null,\"images\":[],\"results\":[{\"url\":\"https://github.com/0xRadi/OWASP-Web-Checklist\",\"title\":\"GitHub - 0xRadi/OWASP-Web-Checklist: OWASP Web Application Security Testing Checklist · GitHub\",\"content\":\"## Navigation Menu. # Search code, repositories, users, issues, pull requests... # Provide feedback. We read every piece of feedback, and take your input very seriously. # Saved searches. ## Use saved searches to filter your results more quickly. To see all available qualifiers, see our documentation. # 0xRadi/OWASP-Web-Checklist. ## Folders and files. | Name | | Name | Last commit message | Last commit date |. | Latest commit   History25 Commits   25 Commits | | |. ## Latest commit. ## Footer. ## Repository files navigation. # OWASP Web Application Security Testing Checklist. ## Table of Contents. ### Information Gathering. ### Configuration Management. ### Secure Transmission. ### Authentication. ### Session Management. ### Data Validation. ### Denial of Service. ### Business Logic. ### Cryptography. ### Risky Functionality - File Uploads. ### Risky Functionality - Card Payment. ### HTML 5. ## History. ### Topics. ### Resources. ### Uh oh! There was an error while loading. ### Watchers. ### Forks. ### Footer navigation.\",\"score\":0.6977124,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://www.aptive.co.uk/blog/owasp-wstg/session-management-testing-checklist\",\"title\":\"OWASP WSTG: Session Management Testing Checklist ✅ - Aptive\",\"content\":\"# OWASP WSTG: Session Management Testing Checklist ✅. Our team have produced the following OWASP WSTG: Session Management Testing Checklist ✅. Our team have produced the following OWASP session management testing checklist based on chapter 4 (web application security testing) of the Web Application Testing Guide (WSTG). The purpose of this checklist is to assist with manual web app security testing when using the OWASP WSTG methodology, each title of this document has been named to reflect that of section 4 from the OWASP WSTG, you can learn more about the documentation structure and see an overview of our OWASP web security testing checklists here. ## 🔐 Testing for Session Management Schema Checklist (WSTG-SESS-01). * Verify that session identifiers are unique and random to prevent session fixation and prediction. * Ensure session tokens are not stored in URLs (e.g., query parameters) to avoid session hijacking. * Verify that session cookies are properly configured with the `HttpOnly` and `Secure` flags to prevent access via JavaScript and ensure secure transmission.\",\"score\":0.69024646,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://hicronsoftware.com/blog/web-app-security-checklist-owasp-top-10\",\"title\":\"Complete Web App Security Checklist Using the OWASP Top 10 | Hicron Software\",\"content\":\"# **Complete Web App Security Checklist Using the OWASP Top 10**. The **Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP) Top 10** is the recognized global standard for pinpointing and neutralizing the most critical security risks web applications face. For anyone in development, security, or compliance, this isn’t just another list of vulnerabilities—it’s the bedrock framework for building secure software. Using the OWASP Top 10 to build a security checklist gives you a systematic, risk-based plan for hardening your applications against common attacks. Key regulations like the **Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS)**, the **General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)**, and the **Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA)** all demand that organizations implement strong security controls. Importance of the OWASP Top 10 for security. **Compliance Impact:** This directly addresses requirements in **PCI DSS 7** (Restrict access to cardholder data by business need to know), **GDPR Article 25** (Data protection by design and by default), and **HIPAA 164.312(a)** (Access control).\",\"score\":0.5530473,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html\",\"title\":\"Session Management - OWASP Cheat Sheet Series\",\"content\":\"+ Session ID Content (or Value). + Session ID Generation and Verification: Permissive and Strict Session Management. + Manage Session ID as Any Other User Input. Therefore, sessions provide the ability to establish variables – such as access rights and localization settings – which will apply to each and every interaction a user has with the web application for the duration of the session. The session ID or token binds the user authentication credentials (in the form of a user session) to the user HTTP traffic and the appropriate access controls enforced by the web application. In order to keep the authenticated state and track the users progress within the web application, applications provide users with a **session identifier** (session ID or token) that is assigned at session creation time, and is shared and exchanged by the user and the web application for the duration of the session (it is sent on every HTTP request).\",\"score\":0.5199851,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@QuarkAndCode/owasp-top-10-cheat-sheet-of-cheat-sheets-for-web-api-security-0366dbba1370\",\"title\":\"OWASP Top 10 Cheat Sheet of Cheat Sheets for Web & API Security | by QuarkAndCode | Medium\",\"content\":\"# OWASP Top 10 Cheat Sheet of Cheat Sheets for Web & API Security. OWASP Top 10 and the Cheat Sheet Series in a Nutshell. **OWASP Top 10** is a consensus list of the most critical web application risks, designed as an awareness and prioritization tool for developers, architects, and security teams. The **OWASP Cheat Sheet Series** turns those abstract risks into **short, focused how‑tos**: secure coding tips, configuration guidance, and decision checklists mapped to each Top 10 category. Broken access control happens when users can perform actions or access data they’re **not supposed** to — viewing someone else’s records, calling admin APIs as a regular user, or forcing access to hidden URLs. * **IDOR (Insecure Direct Object References):** changing an ID in a URL or request body to access someone else’s data. ## Create an account to read the full story. If you’re new to Medium, create a new account to read this story on us.\",\"score\":0.30641338,\"raw_content\":null},{\"url\":\"https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/latest/4-Web_Application_Security_Testing/06-Session_Management_Testing/01-Testing_for_Session_Management_Schema\",\"title\":\"WSTG - Latest | OWASP Foundation\",\"content\":\"One of the core components of any web-based application is the mechanism by which it controls and maintains the state for a user interacting with it. In this test, the tester wants to check that cookies and other session tokens are created in a secure and unpredictable way. In a nutshell, when a user accesses an application which needs to keep track of the actions and identity of that user across multiple requests, a cookie (or cookies) is generated by the server and sent to the client. The data stored in the cookie can provide to the server a large spectrum of information about who the user is, what actions he has performed so far, what his preferences are, etc. Due to the importance of the data that they store, cookies are therefore vital in the overall security of the application. In this test the tester has to check whether the cookies issued to clients can resist a wide range of attacks aimed to interfere with the sessions of legitimate users and with the application itself.\",\"score\":0.2943625,\"raw_content\":null}],\"response_time\":0.77,\"request_id\":\"b6ae6eb2-aa92-42f7-b098-1c8e55ecfcbd\"}"
